title: Bonds up on softer US manufacturing data
text:
Tue, Aug 4, 2015, 9:00 AM AEST - Australia Markets open in 1 hr. Bonds up on softer US manufacturing data AAP â€“ 16 minutes ago Print 
The Australian bond market has rallied overnight on weaker-than-expected US data and continued falls in commodity prices. 
"We've actually outperformed (US) treasuries, but volumes have been pretty thin," National Australia Bank head of interest rate strategy Skye Masters said. 
US ISM manufacturing index missed market estimates when it fell from 53.5 to 52.7 for July, weighed down by the strong greenback. 
"The other data was pretty much in line with expectations but the market seemed to focus on the ISM," Ms Masters said. 
And while the price of iron ore was up, oil and copper prices were down, she said. 
At 0830 AEST on Tuesday, the September 2015 10-year bond futures contract was trading at 97.280 (implying a yield of 2.720 per cent), up from 97.210 (2.790 per cent) on Monday. 
The September 2015 three-year bond futures contract was at 98.140 (1.860 per cent), up from 98.100 (1.900 per cent). 
KEY MOVEMENTS: 
* CGS 5.5pct Jan 2018, 1.865%, unchanged from Friday 
* CGS 4.25pct April 2026, 2.846%, unchanged 
(No trading on Monday due to the bank holiday) 
Sydney Futures Exchange prices: 
* September 2015 bill futures, 97.910 from 97.210 
* December 2015 bill futures, 97.980, from 97.970 
(*Closes taken at 1630 AEST previous local session) 
Source: IRESS
